(Rows may not total to 100% due to rounding)

In 1860 the areas that later formed the 11 Confederate States (and including the future West Virginia) had 132,760 (1.46%) free blacks. Males made up 49.2% of the total population and females 50.8% (whites: 48.60% male, 51.40% female; slaves: 50.15% male, 49.85% female; free blacks: 47.43% male, 52.57% female).<ref>[http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu/php/start.php?year=V1860 All data for this section taken from the University of Virginia Library, Historical Census Browser, Census Data for Year 1860].</ref>

'''Rural/urban configuration'''

The area claimed by the Confederate States of America consisted overwhelmingly of rural land. Few urban areas had populations of more than 1,000&nbsp;– the typical [[county seat]] had a population of fewer than 500 people. Cities were rare. Of the twenty largest U.S. cities in the 1860 census, only [[New Orleans]] lay in Confederate territory<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0027/tab09.txt|title=U.S. Bureau of the Census, Population of the 100 Largest Urban Places: 1860, Internet Release date: June 15, 1998|accessdate=2010-08-29}}</ref>&nbsp;– and the Union captured New Orleans in 1862. Only 13 Confederate-controlled cities ranked among the top 100 U.S. cities in 1860, most of them ports whose economic activities vanished or suffered severely in the [[Union blockade]]. The population of Richmond swelled after it became the Confederate capital, reaching an estimated 128,000 in 1864.<ref>Dabney 1990 p. 182</ref> Other Southern cities in the Border slave-holding states such as [[Maryland in the American Civil War#Maryland's sympathies|Baltimore]] MD, [[Washington, D.C. in the American Civil War|Washington]] DC, [[West Virginia in the American Civil War#Guerrilla war|Wheeling]] VA/WV and [[Alexandria, Virginia#American Civil War|Alexandria]] VA, [[Louisville in the American Civil War|Louisville]] KY, and [[St. Louis in the American Civil War|St. Louis]] MO, never came under the control of the Confederate government.

The cities of the Confederacy included most prominently in order of size of population:

